            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Miriam Wong is San Francisco born and bred, a second-generation native whose identity is as layered as the fog over the Marin Headlands. Her parents, immigrants from Hong Kong, ran a small, bustling grocery store in the Richmond District. Their world was one of pragmatism and long hours, a stark contrast to the world Miriam discovered in the de Young Museum on free Saturdays. While they stocked shelves, she memorized the brushstrokes of Chiura Obata, finding a language for her soul that her practical upbringing couldn't provide.\n\nThis passion led her to UC Berkeley for Art History and then to New York for a graduate degree in Arts Administration, a compromise between her love for art and her parents\u2019 desire for a stable career. Returning to San Francisco was a conscious choice; the East Coast art scene felt too transactional, whereas SF\u2019s felt more intertwined with community and activism. She began as a curatorial assistant at a prominent downtown museum, slowly climbing the ladder through a combination of impeccable scholarship and a quiet, steely determination. Her breakthrough was curating a landmark exhibition on Asian-American post-war abstraction, a project that honored both her profession and her heritage.\n\nNow 49 and the Director of Curatorial Affairs, Miriam\u2019s life has found a comfortable rhythm. A past long-term relationship ended a decade ago, leaving her single but not lonely, her life rich with a close circle of friends, artists, and prot\u00e9g\u00e9s. Her daily routine begins in her well-kept Inner Richmond flat, surrounded by books and catalogs. The 38-Geary bus is her mobile office, a 3.8-mile journey where she reviews proposals and catches up on art world news before a day of managing budgets, artists, and egos.\n\nHer connection to the city is visceral\u2014it\u2019s in the taste of dim sum from her childhood haunts, the solitary walks through Golden Gate Park, and the familiar rumble of the Muni. Miriam\u2019s ambition is no longer about climbing higher, but about creating a legacy. Her dream is to secure a permanent endowment for emerging Bay Area artists of color, ensuring that the next generation of storytellers has the support her parents, for all their love, could never have imagined providing."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was ten, escaping the scent of dried fish and cardboard boxes for the de Young\u2019s hushed halls. She stood before Chiura Obata\u2019s \"Moonlight, High Sierra,\" and the world fell silent. The ink wash of the mountains felt more real than the stacked cans at her parents' store. It wasn't just a picture; it was a language she understood instinctively. In that moment, art became her private sanctuary, a truth she would spend her life defending, first to her parents, and then to the world.\n\n2.\nIt was during a slow afternoon at the store when she was nineteen. She told her father she was declaring Art History as her major. He didn\u2019t yell. He just stopped stacking oranges, his back to her, and sighed. The weight of his disappointment felt heavier than any textbook. But in that silence, a stubborn resolve settled in her bones. She would not just love art; she would prove its worth, turning his pragmatism into a silent challenge she had to meet on her own terms.\n\n3.\nThe gallery was buzzing on the opening night of her Asian-American abstraction show. She was in her late thirties. An elderly Chinese couple, who reminded her so much of her parents, stood mesmerized before a bold canvas. The woman turned to her husband and whispered something in Cantonese, her eyes alight with recognition. Seeing them, Miriam felt a profound click. Her two worlds\u2014the daughter of immigrants and the museum curator\u2014had finally fused. It was a moment of absolute, quiet vindication.\n\n4.\nA month after her partner moved out, when she was thirty-nine, she took a walk through the Japanese Tea Garden. The quiet precision of the place echoed a new feeling inside her. She sat by the koi pond, not waiting for anyone, just watching the fish drift. There was a clean, sharp ache of loss, but underneath it, the sturdy foundation of her own life. She realized she was not half of a whole, but complete on her own. Solitude became a strength, not a circumstance.\n\n5.\nA few years ago, riding the 38-Geary home, she saw a young woman sketching furiously in a notebook, her paint-stained fingers clutching a portfolio that had seen better days. Miriam saw a flicker of her younger self in the woman\u2019s fierce concentration, a hunger that funding and connections could either nurture or starve. The thought wasn't academic; it was a visceral pull. Her own ambition suddenly seemed small. The need for the endowment wasn't just a goal; it became a responsibility."
